    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#maffre2007"/>, p. 181, n. <citedRange>51</citedRange>, fig. 21 (ph.)</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>57.2002, 16</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>108300</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
              </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><w lemma="δεκάτα"><expan><abbr>Δεκά</abbr><ex>τα</ex></expan></w>
                </ab></div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p>
                    <app loc="1">
                        <lem><expan><abbr>Δεκά</abbr><ex>τα</ex></expan></lem>
                        <rdg resp="#maffre2007">δέκα</rdg></app>
                </p>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Dîme.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Tithe.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Decima.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>A reading <foreign>δέκα</foreign> would provide a well-formed Greek word, possibly meaningful as a trademark inscribed in full (price or number of items
                    in a bunch?). However, the fragment being stored amidst dedications of the tithe, it is more plausible to read it as an abbreviation. Such is perhaps
                the case also at <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr107900</ref>. <bibl><ptr target="#rosamilia2023"/>, p. <citedRange>87</citedRange>, footnote 28</bibl> also prefers 
                an abbreviated mention of tithe.</p>
                <p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
